TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Adoption Of Institutionally Contested Organizational Practices: The Emergence Of Stock Option Pay In Germany
AU  - Sanders, WM. Gerard
AU  - Tuschke, Anja
Y1  - 2007/02/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2007.24160889
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2007.24160889
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 33
EP  - 56
VL  - 50
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Examining the transnational diffusion of organizational practices from institutional environments in which they are legitimate to environments in which key institutional actors contest them, we contrast processes facilitating pioneering adoptions of contested practices with processes that diffuse the contested practices. Courageous adopters of contested practices are likely to have (1) exposure to high-status institutional environments in which the practices are legitimate and (2) experience with other contested practices. Regulatory legitimization and institutional isomorphism processes then diffuse the contested practices within an environment. The results of a study of stock option pay adoption among large German firms generally support our hypotheses.
AB  - Examining the transnational diffusion of organizational practices from institutional environments in which they are legitimate to environments in which key institutional actors contest them, we contrast processes facilitating pioneering adoptions of contested practices with processes that diffuse the contested practices. Courageous adopters of contested practices are likely to have (1) exposure to high-status institutional environments in which the practices are legitimate and (2) experience with other contested practices. Regulatory legitimization and institutional isomorphism processes then diffuse the contested practices within an environment. The results of a study of stock option pay adoption among large German firms generally support our hypotheses.
